SIMPLE: profanation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Profanation
<hw>Prof`a*na"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>profanatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>profanation</ets>. See
<er>Profane</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of
violating sacred things, or of treating them with contempt or
irreverence; irreverent or too familiar treatment or use of what is
sacred; desecration; <as>as, the <ex>profanation</ex> of the Sabbath;
the <ex>profanation</ex> of a sanctuary; the <ex>profanation</ex> of the
name of God.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act of treating with abuse or disrespect, or
with undue publicity, or lack of delicacy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>'T were <qex>profanation</qex> of our joys⟦br⟧
To tell the laity our love.</q> <rj><qau>Donne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Profane</ent>⟦br⟧
